        public boolean disallowChanges()

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(java.lang.Object anotherSet)
        Compares two ComparableSet objects lexically.

        This is the definition of lexical ordering. If two sets are different then the disjunction of those two sets is not empty. Let k be the smallest element in that disjunction. Then the set not containing k lexically precedes the other set.

        Thus, a subset always lexically precedes its superset. However, the converse is not true, i.e. the lexically smaller set is not always a subset of a set that is lexically greater.

        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface ComparableSet
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable
        Parameters:
        anotherSet - the ComparableSet to be compared.
        Returns:
        the value 0 if the argument set is equal to this set; a value less than zero if this set is lexically smaller than the argument set; a value greater than zero if this set is lexically greater than the argument set.

      • clone

        public java.lang.Object clone()
        Creates and returns a copy of this ComparableSet.

        The purpose of this method is to create a copy of a ComparableHashSet that is itself an instance of ComparableHashSet.

        If it is not necessary that the copy is an instance of ComparableHashSet it is recommended not to use this method but a constructor of a class that implements java.util.Collection instead. For example, a copy of the ComparableHashSet cs can be created using Set copy = new HashSet(cs) rather than Set copy = cs.clone() if the copy does not need to be an instance of ComparableHashSet.

        Specified by:
        clone in interface ComparableSet
        Overrides:
        clone in class java.util.HashSet<java.lang.Comparable>
        Returns:
        a copy of this instance that is not write protected.
        See Also:
        Collection
